1
00:00:02,291 --> 00:00:10,055
[SPEAKER_04]: What is the most important political economy obstacle standing in the way and how can it be overcome?

2
00:00:10,195 --> 00:00:17,598
[SPEAKER_04]: Can you hear me?

3
00:00:17,938 --> 00:00:19,919
[SPEAKER_00]: Okay, so I do have better luck.

4
00:00:20,439 --> 00:00:25,922
[SPEAKER_00]: So let me start by saying a very big thank you to the African Development Bank, UNECA,

5
00:00:26,702 --> 00:00:31,624
[SPEAKER_00]: UNDP and OECD for the invitation to join this discussion today.

6
00:00:32,324 --> 00:00:41,968
[SPEAKER_00]: So Raymond, in response to your question, I don't think there is a single obstacle per se, and also not all the barriers are necessarily political economy.

7
00:00:42,589 --> 00:00:50,012
[SPEAKER_00]: Let me start with one barrier, domestic resource mobilization, which Professor Orama spoke about earlier on.

8
00:00:50,052 --> 00:00:53,133
[SPEAKER_00]: This is a classical political economy challenge.

9
00:00:53,733 --> 00:00:55,514
[SPEAKER_00]: Wealthier, well-connected Africa

10
00:00:57,878 --> 00:00:58,899
[SPEAKER_00]: to pay more taxes.

11
00:00:59,759 --> 00:01:08,025
[SPEAKER_00]: Can you hear me?

12
00:01:10,047 --> 00:01:11,868
[SPEAKER_00]: Okay, let's try.

13
00:01:13,029 --> 00:01:13,689
[SPEAKER_00]: Okay, great.

14
00:01:14,450 --> 00:01:21,175
[SPEAKER_00]: Okay, so politicians are often reluctant to charge more taxes to citizens.

15
00:01:22,336 --> 00:01:25,098
[SPEAKER_00]: But as Professor Rama showed earlier on,

16
00:01:25,706 --> 00:01:37,729
[SPEAKER_00]: Citizens in most African countries are willing to pay more tax if they can see the link between their taxes and robust services.

17
00:01:38,690 --> 00:01:42,351
[SPEAKER_00]: So it's not that these barriers cannot be overcome.

18
00:01:42,391 --> 00:01:44,851
[SPEAKER_00]: They can be overcome, and we've seen them in countries.

19
00:01:44,911 --> 00:01:52,614
[SPEAKER_00]: So we've seen them in Rwanda, where the government of Rwanda increased its tax to GDP ratio from just under 10% in 2000

20
00:01:54,438 --> 00:01:56,760
[SPEAKER_00]: to 16.2% in 2022.

21
00:01:57,200 --> 00:02:01,243
[SPEAKER_00]: And Senegal is approaching almost 20% of tax to GDP ratio.

22
00:02:02,224 --> 00:02:09,729
[SPEAKER_00]: And they've done this through reforms in digital tax administration and electronic taxpayer registration.

23
00:02:10,309 --> 00:02:16,794
[SPEAKER_00]: And in Rwanda, citizens can see a link between the taxes they are paying and the services that they are receiving.

24
00:02:17,634 --> 00:02:22,778
[SPEAKER_00]: Now, some of the challenges are less about politics and more about coordination.

25
00:02:23,318 --> 00:02:32,841
[SPEAKER_00]: So we often criticize international investors for not investing in Africa and saying that Africa is too risky.

26
00:02:33,361 --> 00:02:36,842
[SPEAKER_00]: But sometimes we must put the mirror in our own faces.

27
00:02:36,862 --> 00:02:44,244
[SPEAKER_00]: We have the same challenges with our own institutional investors who do not invest in the continent enough.

28
00:02:44,384 --> 00:02:49,646
[SPEAKER_00]: So in my own country, Ghana, pension funds are allowed to invest

29
00:02:50,590 --> 00:02:55,312
[SPEAKER_00]: up to 25% of their portfolios in alternative assets.

30
00:02:55,832 --> 00:02:57,932
[SPEAKER_00]: Do you wanna guess how much is elevated right now?

31
00:02:58,513 --> 00:02:59,393
[SPEAKER_00]: Less than 1%.

32
00:03:00,773 --> 00:03:03,934
[SPEAKER_00]: So this is not a regulatory challenge, okay?

33
00:03:05,014 --> 00:03:10,116
[SPEAKER_00]: It is a deeply ingrained sense of conservatism.

34
00:03:10,916 --> 00:03:13,537
[SPEAKER_00]: That means that they are not making these investments.

35
00:03:14,017 --> 00:03:16,358
[SPEAKER_00]: And Ghanaian fund managers tell me all the time

36
00:03:16,938 --> 00:03:17,938
[SPEAKER_00]: They want to hit 5%.

37
00:03:18,119 --> 00:03:20,119
[SPEAKER_00]: They don't even want to get to 2% or 10%.

38
00:03:20,139 --> 00:03:26,602
[SPEAKER_00]: If they could get to 5%, the amount of money that would be released would be substantial for Ghana's development.

39
00:03:27,503 --> 00:03:30,824
[SPEAKER_00]: The third challenge is coordination around financial institutions.

40
00:03:30,864 --> 00:03:34,246
[SPEAKER_00]: And again, Professor Rama alluded to this earlier on.

41
00:03:34,666 --> 00:03:43,730
[SPEAKER_00]: You know, we have frameworks like the African Alliance of Multilateral Financial Institutions, and now we know a lot about NAFA as well.

42
00:03:44,438 --> 00:03:52,262
[SPEAKER_00]: Now the idea is that if financial institutions can collaborate, they can leverage their balance sheet substantially.

43
00:03:52,282 --> 00:04:00,227
[SPEAKER_00]: Unfortunately, different governance structures, shareholder interest, and capital constraints make this very difficult.

44
00:04:00,687 --> 00:04:07,210
[SPEAKER_00]: So being able to get over this process will be substantially beneficial to the continent.

45
00:04:07,270 --> 00:04:12,173
[SPEAKER_00]: So ANSI, for example, has a balance sheet of 70 billion.

46
00:04:12,513 --> 00:04:13,634
[SPEAKER_00]: If they could collaborate,

47
00:04:14,274 --> 00:04:20,699
[SPEAKER_00]: they believe that they could leverage these as organisations and invest in the African continent.

48
00:04:21,579 --> 00:04:34,189
[SPEAKER_00]: But if I were to pick one, I would say that our single biggest political economy challenge would be elite capture and political settlements.

49
00:04:35,630 --> 00:04:41,454
[SPEAKER_00]: And until we can deal with the challenges around elite capture and political settlements,

50
00:04:41,930 --> 00:04:47,294
[SPEAKER_00]: that benefit the minority at the expense of the majority, we are not going to get over it.

51
00:04:47,534 --> 00:04:56,760
[SPEAKER_00]: So politicians, politically connected businesses and vested interests often benefit from shallow relationship-based financial systems.

52
00:04:57,221 --> 00:05:02,604
[SPEAKER_00]: And they resist the kind of reforms that would reduce their influence in the financial space.

53
00:05:02,624 --> 00:05:04,225
[SPEAKER_00]: So let me give you one example.

54
00:05:04,906 --> 00:05:10,750
[SPEAKER_00]: In 2017, some of you would have heard of the financial institutions crisis that Ghana faced.

55
00:05:11,774 --> 00:05:21,017
[SPEAKER_00]: Now, with regulatory failures and insider lending, the Central Bank of Ghana ultimately was forced to do a cleanup.

56
00:05:21,777 --> 00:05:25,418
[SPEAKER_00]: And do you want to guess what this cleanup cost us?

57
00:05:25,438 --> 00:05:27,258
[SPEAKER_00]: 7 to 8% of our GDP.

58
00:05:28,119 --> 00:05:29,099
[SPEAKER_00]: That's what it cost us.

59
00:05:29,279 --> 00:05:39,902
[SPEAKER_00]: Now, knowing this, this is a good illustration of why financial sector reform is politically difficult, but it's economically essential.

60
00:05:48,770 --> 00:06:13,727
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you so much for those very excellent points, and also the reality check around maybe we need to look inside the continent, we need to see and answer the question why institutions do have the ability to basically invest, not investing, and also the small matter of the need to capture and go into the settlements.

61
00:06:14,407 --> 00:06:17,349
[SPEAKER_04]: I think I'll go next to you, Mr. Kuteli.

62
00:06:18,910 --> 00:06:36,923
[SPEAKER_04]: And could we pose a question about how should the African Development Bank use its balance sheet and other instruments to shape markets in which African institutions need transactions rather than remain absolutely public?

63
00:06:39,225 --> 00:06:39,865
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

64
